metadata.name: Attractor #203
metadata.description:
People are often drawn together over shared interest, and through their connections to those interests they find connections with others. Attractor is a visualization of community, a central interest bringing people together, pushing past their walls, bad habits, and traumas. The image is meant to be deceiving in its focus on the attractor, where the true focus is on the overlaps and complex defenses we build around ourselves. Those defenses can make us and those connections into more beautiful, ornate structures, or keep us distant from those around us. Sometimes focusing on a shared attractor is the only way we can let down our guard.

Press ‚Äôs‚Äô to save a .png
Press ‚Äôt‚Äô to toggle the grain for printing or personal preference
Press ‚Äòp‚Äô to save a higher quality .png
Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Florescence #166
metadata.description:
Digitally crafted flowers in pots for virtual window sills.

In the spirit of the piranha plant from the Mario Bros videogame. We wanted to create a project that acknowledges the playful depiction of nature in early videogames by creating a retro futuristic collectible that explores aesthetics over gameplay, whilst preserving the playful energy of these early digital worlds. There are many game elements that have emerged over the years that have become iconic in their own right. Their memorable designs have come to represent the exciting feeling of when we first discovered these worlds, but over time an appreciation for their simple design execution, harmony and balance has emerged. Art can exist in many forms and places including a digital pot plant.

Rarity:

There are a total of 23 hand-drawn and animated sprites divided into 4 groups Firelillies, Flytraps, Quasars and Stargazers and there are 15 possible combinations made from these 4 groups. 18% of the collection is a combination of these 4 groups which we can call random and the remaining 72% is divided between the remaining 14 combinations.


There are 3 possible grid systems 1x1, 3x3 and 4x4 

3% 1x1

40% 3x3

57% 4x4



There are 14 possible placement points for all grids and 76 stem/sprite arragement in total



For the pots and stems there are 11 colors to choose and  no rarities for color combinations.



The flower distribution can be either symmetric or random. 35% symmetric and 65% random



Export options:

Pressing 's' on desktop or holding for 2 seconds will download gif to whatever the current device resolution is. To export at a different resolution open the token in new window by clicking 'open' link under the token image and add "&exportsize=1080" or "&exportsize=2160" to end of the url and hit enter then either hold for 2 seconds or press 's' to create gif and download.

metadata.description:

The center of a digital, quantified space emits 2 560 000 particles through a sequence of expansions, contractions and perturbations. üåå

Once formed, the evolution of the Univercell can be observed through a series of animations in the manner of a documentary. üé•

-----
* Mint preview *

Minter will get a 1920x1920 PNG bitmap and an infinite animation.

-----
* Technics *

This experience is designed to be executed on a recent GPU (>2016) and displayed on 16/9 screens from FHD to 8K+ (1920x1080 ‚Üí 7680x4320) at 60FPS for infinite duration.

The physics algorithms take around 20 seconds to generate one Univercell. During generation, a progress indication in percentage is displayed.

- JavaScript / ThreeJS / WebGL
- Unique generative and determinist animation (animation is seeded by the fxhash mint hash)
- Unlimited duration (no loop) / 6 documentary animations
- 20 seconds internal algorithm variations

-----
* Controls *

Keyboard "Space" : take a PNG capture of the current view frame (same ratio as window, max 1920x1080)

‚öó Empiric mode (empiric=on / see URL modifiers below)
Wheel/pinch : zoom in/out to observe the Univercell on different scales
Right click + drag : move the observation area
Keyboard "R" : enable automatic rotation of view

-----
* URL modifiers *

"&empiric=on"
Turn off animations and display a Univercell that can be manually explored.

"&demo=on"
Reduce the cinematics duration to 5 seconds. Allows faster cycling through documentary phases.

"&random=on"
Randomize documentary sequences order.


-----

metadata.name: cliques #50
metadata.description:
clique is defined as:

- /klƒìk,klik/ (n.) a small group of people, with shared interests or other features in common, who spend time together and do not readily allow others to join them.

cliques can offer safety. (something about numbers.)

cliques can offer a place to be. (for better or worse.)

sometimes cliques have sub-cliques. (the intersections can get a bit complicated.)

sometimes a member of a clique may still feel outside of it. (power dynamics can ruin things.)

occasionally clique dynamics are balanced and the connections between the members pull towards the center. (we can consider that non-toxic.)

often, though, the connections are pulled in various directions and the connection between two members are swayed (or pulled towards) other members. (we can consider that toxic.)

[4 color palettes: monochrome, neon, vibrant rebellion, glacier]

[tap ‚Äús‚Äù to save image]
[tip: zoom out to 25% first to save a higher res image]

metadata.name: Terra Nova #118
metadata.description:
In the year 2250, the first galactic sector stretching a few hundred parsecs were mapped and new worlds identified for the upcoming Terraforming missions. Who knows what one may stumble across wondering across the stars. Some of these planets feel at home, some feel off while the rest seem ALIVE. Part of the Terra universe

This piece consists of 6 layers driven by controlled noise to create different structures without the use of any external textures.

Keypress

metadata.name: Uninhabitable #175
metadata.description:
Uninhabitable is a generative system built only from ellipses. The process of playing with different geometric and trigonometric disruptions gives rise to four different compositions which seek to evoque living constructions and environments. Besides the shape itself and its related distortion, the stroke weight of the lines plays a meaningful role in the piece. Following a discrete range [0.01,0.1,1] the weight reveals the process allowing the viewer to realize the trace of the huge amount of lines in each piece. This back and forth between scales and context is, while kind of stripping the code, part of my continuing interest on understanding the -usually- crazy paths of machines' way of thinking.

Press "h" to see it and high resolution and refresh to get back to the initial state. Press "h" to save it.

Uninhabitable is an original work by Iskra Velitchkova. 2021.

metadata.name: AUTOJOURNEYPAINT #206
metadata.description:
An automatic painting journey

AUTOJOURNEYPAINT  uses a series of custom built walkers to make plots with a great variety of properties, including packing gaps, directions and propensity for turning. These plots are then drawn over with varying, incremented pixel brushes.

AUTOJOURNEYPAINT chooses color for itself from a broad list of more than 100 colors. It selects a palette of 8 but might not use all of them.

The background consists of a single color at the back and then one channel (either r, g, b) of the same color iterating from 0 to 255 while also iterating over a number of pixels within a border, all fixed to a pixel grid of variable size. The iteration over pixel numbers means the background produces very different patterns at different screen sizes

If you want to know more about the variables used they are output in the console log

Responsive to screen size. Larger resolutions will implement more brush strokes.

Some renders may be slower due to more complex collision detection in some brush settings.

Press ‚Äús‚Äù to save the image as a png.

metadata.name: The Past Ahead #132
metadata.description:
Cyanotypes once were the most advanced technology to create images. When I see one today I look at it as a beautiful relic and I can't help but put my present in perspective. In these uncertain times the technologies we use to create are threatened with sudden extinction. But I feel joy in imagining our works joining the strata of history, a fallen species, the breeding ground of creations to come.

metadata.name: sketch: cairn() #30
metadata.description:
A cairn is a monument made of stacked rocks. In modern times, often used for wayfinding in remote areas, as in mountaineering, or to indicate an area of significance.

In this sketch I imagine these monuments -- through the looking glass. Paying mind to the simplicity of their construction, as well as the mysticism of what each might represent.

---

Sketch is a series meant to celebrate learning and experimentation.

In this sketch I experiment with subdivision, smoothing, textures, multiple levels of domain warping, and illustration techniques.

---
- Made with p5js
- Press s to save png
- Use param ?width=x to render at size

metadata.name: Enfantines II. Enfantillages Pittoresques #23
metadata.description:
The Enfantines¬†are three sets of beginner piano pieces by¬†Erik Satie, written with the aim of preparing children for the sound patterns of modern music. Composed in 1913, these are genuine children‚Äôs pieces, crafted for small hands, easy to learn. 

‚ÄúEnfantines II. Enfantillages Pittoresques‚Äù is the second of a set of algorithms that explore the basics of Generative Art, written with the aim of preparing artists for the script patterns of digital life. ‚ÄúEnfantillages Pittoresques‚Äù experiments with predefined plots, colour blending, webgl shaders, and generative music; all with a fresh, childish style. This algorithm has been trained to draw basic shapes in accordance to Satie‚Äôs lyrics. However, it uses them in unusual ways and creates what looks like fantastic creatures, microscopic beings, or, to follow Corneille, Constant, and Appel: "human animals".

‚ÄúIt took me four years to paint like Raphael, but a lifetime to paint like a child‚Äù Attributed to Picasso (falsely, probably)

With two modes that won‚Äôt produce the same outputs, ‚ÄúEnfantines‚Äù are best experienced twice. In music mode, the code uses Satie‚Äôs piano composition as a way of taming randomness, the sounds affecting the parameters of the strokes.

Hey, these have won me congratulations from the Shah of Persia and the King of Yvetot!


# INTERACTIVITY
Press M or Double Tap (mobile) for AUDIO mode
Wait for SILENT mode
Press I for Trait Info (desktop)
Press 1 for Canvas Save (desktop)

Introduce ‚Äú?pixelDensity=171‚Äù after URL for FULL SCREEN MODE (pseudo-deterministic).
Introduce ‚Äú?pixelDensity=X‚Äù for HQ renders (standard is 2, and 8 produces 400ppi 40x44cm prints).


# EASY-TO-READ CODE
The ‚ÄúEnfantines‚Äù are educational algorithms. The code has been compressed and minified for a performance boost, but can be read fully in GitHub: https://github.com/ratchitect/


# PERFORMANCE
Better experienced with Chrome.
